    <title>Derivative</title>
    <url>/2022/11/25/Derivative/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<h3 id="definition">Definition</h3>
<p>Instantaneous rate of change at the point of the function.
Presentation in Math,<span
class="math inline">\(f&#39;(c)=\lim\limits_{h\to0}\dfrac {f(c+h)-f(c)}
h\)</span>, the tangent line of <span class="math inline">\(f\)</span>
at <span class="math inline">\(c\)</span> will go through <span
class="math inline">\((c,f(c))\)</span>, the equation is <span
class="math inline">\(l(x)=f&#39;(c)(x-c)+f(c)\)</span>.</p>
<p>If we draw the derivatives of each point in the graph, we can get a
new function called the derivative function, the equation is <span
class="math inline">\(f&#39;(x)=\lim\limits_{h\to0}\dfrac {f(x+h)-f(x)}
h\)</span>, It also writen as <span
class="math inline">\(f&#39;(x)=y&#39;=\dfrac {dy} {dx}=\dfrac {df}
{dx}=\dfrac d {dx}(y)=\dfrac d {dx}(f)\)</span></p>
<h3 id="common-drtivative-functions">Common Drtivative Functions</h3>
<p><span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
&amp;\frac d {dx}(c) = 0 \qquad &amp;\frac d {dx}(ax) = a\\
&amp;\frac d {dx}(x^n) = nx^{n-1} \qquad &amp;\frac d {dx}(e^x) = e^x\\
&amp;\frac d {dx}(sinx) = cosx \qquad &amp;\frac d {dx}(cosx) = -sinx\\
&amp;\frac d {dx}(tanx) = sec^2x \qquad &amp;\frac d {dx}(lnx) = \frac 1
x\\
&amp;\frac d {dx}(a^x) = a^xlna \qquad &amp;\frac d{dx}(x^x) =
x^x(lnx+1)
\end{aligned}
\]</span></p>
<h3 id="provertives-of-drivatives">Provertives of Drivatives</h3>
<p><span class="math display">\[
\text{Sum Rule:}\hfill \\
\frac d {dx}(f(x)\pm g(x)) = \frac d {dx}(f(x))\pm \frac d
{dx}(g(x))=f&#39;(x) \pm g&#39;(x)\\
\text{Constant Multiple Rule:}\hfill \\
\frac d {dx}(cf(x)) = c\frac d {dx}(f(x)) = cf&#39;(x)\hfill \\
\text{Product Rule:}\hfill\\
\frac d {dx}(f(x)g(x)) = f&#39;(x)g(x)+f(x)g&#39;(x)\hfill\\
\text{Quotient Rule:}\hfill \\
\frac d {dx}(\frac {f(x)} {g(x)}) = \frac {f&#39;(x)g(x)-f(x)g&#39;(x)}
{g^2(x)} \hfill
\]</span></p>
<h3 id="chain-rule">Chain Rule</h3>
<p><span class="math inline">\(f\circ g=f(g(x))\)</span> means the
composition of <span class="math inline">\(f(x)\)</span> and <span
class="math inline">\(g(x)\)</span>, the range of <span
class="math inline">\(g(x)\)</span> is the interval of <span
class="math inline">\(f(x)\)</span>.</p>
<p>If we want to get the dervative of <span
class="math inline">\(y=f(g(x))\)</span>, use the <strong>chain
rule</strong>:</p>
<p><span class="math inline">\(y&#39;=f&#39;(g(x))\cdot g(x)\)</span>,
we often use <span class="math inline">\(u=g(x)\)</span> to present it:
<span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
&amp;\frac d {dy} u^n = n(u)^{n-1}\cdot u&#39; \qquad &amp;\frac d {dy}
cosu = -sinu\cdot u&#39;\\
&amp;\frac d {dy} e^{u} = e^u\cdot u&#39;\qquad &amp;\frac d {dy} tanu =
sec^2u\cdot u&#39;\\
&amp;\frac d {dy} sinu = cosu\cdot u&#39;\\
\end{aligned}
\]</span></p>
<h3 id="implicit-diﬀerentiation">Implicit Diﬀerentiation</h3>
<p>We have known <span class="math inline">\(\dfrac d {dx} f(g(x)) =
f&#39;(g(x))\cdot g&#39;(x)\)</span>, let <span
class="math inline">\(y=g(x)\)</span>, we can write as <span
class="math inline">\(\dfrac d {dx} f(y) = f&#39;(y)\cdot
y&#39;=f&#39;(y) \dfrac {dy} {dx}\)</span></p>
<p>For instance, how to get <span class="math inline">\(y&#39;\)</span>
of the function <span class="math inline">\(x^2+y^2=1\)</span>? <span
class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
&amp;(x^2+y^2)&#39;=1&#39;\\
&amp;2x+2y\cdot y&#39;=0 \qquad.......\text{Let $f(y)=y^2$}\\
&amp;y&#39;=-\frac y x
\end{aligned}
\]</span></p>
<h3 id="inverse-function">Inverse Function</h3>
<p>Let <span class="math inline">\(f(x)\)</span>and <span
class="math inline">\(g(x)\)</span> be two <strong>one-to-one</strong>
functions. If <span class="math inline">\((f\circ
g)(x)=f(g(x))=x\)</span> then we say that <span
class="math inline">\(f(x)\)</span> and <span
class="math inline">\(g(x)\)</span> are inverses of each other. We
denote <span class="math inline">\(g(x)\)</span> (the inverse of <span
class="math inline">\(f(x)\)</span> by <span
class="math inline">\(g(x)=f^{−1}(x)\)</span>.</p>
<p>*** Attention: <span class="math inline">\(f^{-1}(x) \neq \dfrac 1
{f(x)}\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(f^{-1}\)</span> is a symbol
not a exponentiation.***</p>
<p>Let <span class="math inline">\(y=g(x)\)</span> and we have know
<span class="math inline">\(f(y)=x\)</span> so that <span
class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
\dfrac d {dx} f(y) &amp;= \dfrac d {dx} x\\
f&#39;(y)\cdot y&#39; &amp;= 1\\
y&#39; &amp;=\frac 1 {f&#39;(y)}\\
y&#39;&amp;=(f^{-1})&#39;(x)=g&#39;(x)=\frac 1 {f&#39;(g(x))}
\end{aligned}
\]</span></p>
<h3 id="common-inverse-drtivative-functions">Common Inverse Drtivative
Functions</h3>
<p><span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
&amp;\frac d {dx}(sin^{-1}x) = \dfrac 1 {\sqrt {1-x^2}} \qquad
&amp;\frac d {dx}(cos^{-1}x) = -\dfrac 1 {\sqrt {1-x^2}}\\
&amp;\frac d {dx}(tan^{-1}x) = \dfrac 1 {1+x^2} \qquad
\end{aligned}
\]</span></p>
]]></content>
      <categories>
        <category>Calculus</category>
      </categories>
      <tags>
        <tag>Derivatives of function</tag>
      </tags>
